    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Wendy's Massacre: Death Penalty Issue</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John E Colbert letter opposes death penalty for killers of five people at a Wendy's restaurant in Flushing, Queens</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Queens, Shock at a Methodical Massacre of 5'' (front page, May 26):</p>
        <p>When we consider the deliberate and calculated execution of these murders, the horrific last moments of the victims, the ready alternatives to their deaths and the lifelong anguish of their families, we are uniformly appalled.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Queens, Shock at a Methodical Massacre of 5'' (front page, May 26):</p>
        <p>When we consider the deliberate and calculated execution of these murders, the horrific last moments of the victims, the ready alternatives to their deaths and the lifelong anguish of their families, we are uniformly appalled.</p>
        <p>Shouldn't the more deliberate and calculated planning by the state, the similarly horrific last moments of the condemned killers, the ready alternatives to their deaths and the lifelong anguish of their families -- should the State of New York eventually execute the killers -- cause us to be appalled, as well?</p>
        <p>JOHN E. COLBERT  Chicago, May 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
